Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,35,", not only in Asia but also in Africa (Arkell 1936; Sleen 1958; 204, fig.l). Recent archaeological research in Indonesia has yielded a number of glass and stone beads in several prehistoric sites, including the caves of Leang Buidane in the Talaud Islands, (Bellwood 1976), Leang Bua on Flores, and Camplong in West Timor (Ratna Indraningsih 1985: 134-5, fig.l). Beside beads, several vessels believed to be southern or eastern Indian rouletted ware hav",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,37,"Kidul (Hoop 1935) and Plawangan (Sukendar and Awe 1981) in Central Java; Kidangan/Kawengan (Suryanto 1985) and Besuki (Heekeren 1958) in East Java; Gunung Piring in Lombok (Gunadi 1978); Melolo in Sumba (Heekeren 1956); Leang Buidane in the Talaud Islands (Bellwood 1976, 1984); Leang Bua in Flores; and Camplong cave in Timor (Ratna Indraningsih 1985). These wide occurrences of beads in the Indonesian archipelago might one day be able to indicate the",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,37,"Central Java; Kidangan/Kawengan (Suryanto 1985) and Besuki (Heekeren 1958) in East Java; Gunung Piring in Lombok (Gunadi 1978); Melolo in Sumba (Heekeren 1956); Leang Buidane in the Talaud Islands (Bellwood 1976, 1984); Leang Bua in Flores; and Camplong cave in Timor (Ratna Indraningsih 1985). These wide occurrences of beads in the Indonesian archipelago might one day be able to indicate the trade routes and processes of early Indian contacts.",Leang Bua,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,39,"ology, through comparative studies of other sites which have produced bronze and iron objects, as well as glass and stone beads. Such sites include Gilimanuk, in Bali^Pejaten and Pasir Angin/Leuwiliang in West Java, and Leang Buidane in the Talaud Islands of northeastern Indonesia. In addition, a comparative study will also be undertaken on other relevant sites in Southeast Asia. Gilimanuk is the only site in Bali to have been dated by the radiocarb",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,40,"he resolution of this dating problem is not yet clear. The site may have been used as a ceremonial offering place between about 1000 BC and AD 1000 (Sutayasa 1979: 69; Bellwood 1978: 224-225). Archaeological research in Leang Buidane in the Talaud Islands has produced jar burials associated with offerings of pottery, beads, baked clay casting moulds, and metal artifacts (Bellwood 1976; 1978; 1985: 305-309). The large burial jars at Leang Buidane wer",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,41,"The spherical carnelian beads range from 4 to 16 mm in diameter, but only three exceed 8 mm, and seven of the total of twelve spherical carnelians have diameters of only 4-5 mm. Bellwood believes that all the beads from Leang Buidane might have been imported from India, although fragments of carnelian beads which may come from a workshop have been found at Kuala Selinsing in Perak, West Malaysia (1976; 276). Facetted carnelian beads have a very wide",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,42,"35 calculated as 960 years BP. In addition, iron objects also occur in Leang Buidane, including a tang for a knife or spearhead, and two other small rodlike fragments. On the basis of these dates Bellwood places the Leang Buidane assemblage between 700 and 1500 AD, or earlier (1976: 278: 1985: 307). Rec",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Leang Buidane,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/BronzeArt_Bali.pdf,43,"36 As already noted, the assemblages from Agop Atas and Leang Buidane seem to parallel those of the Early Metal phase in the Philippines, particularly Kalanay and the Tabon caves. Unfortunately, only Manunggul Chamber B at Tabon cave has a relevant radiocarbon date in this case, of about",Leang Buidane,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,4,"or), and received much support from Pak Dikdik (Geology Museum). From ARKENAS (Jakarta), 1 would like to thank Thomas Sutikna, Jatmiko, and Wayhu Saptomo for their friendship and assistance during my times in Ruteng and Liang Bua. 1 am also grateful to my friend, Jublina Tode, for her enthusiasm in the field and love of Kupang food. My Ngada co-excavators were a constant source of amusement and cultural exegesis during my fieldwork in the Soa, n",Liang Bua,duplicate,
