Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,200,. The aim is to build as detailed a picture as possible of Pleistocene stone technology in Southeast Asia. Particular emphasis will be placed on drawing comparisons between the Mata Menge and the chronologically younger Liang Bua stone assemblage from Flores. 9.2 New Southeast Asian data The 800-880 kya Mata Menge stone flaking technology was based on the bifacial radial reduction of cobbles and medium-sized flake blanks. These artefacts were ca,Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,201,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 The largest, most well-dated and meticulously analysed Pleistocene stone assemblage from Southeast Asia is the lithic assemblage from Liang Bua cave in western Flores (see Moore 2003d, 2004, 2005a-b, in press; Moore and Brumm 2004, 2007; Morwood e! al. 2004, 2005; Brumm et al. 2006). In addition to Mata Menge and Liang Bua—the earliest well-documented stone art",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua Cave,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,201,"res. This chapter begins with a discussion of the Liang Bua stone technology, and concludes with a comparison of this evidence with the stone technology from Mata Menge and other Pleistocene sites in Southeast Asia. 9.3 Liang Bua Cave 9.3.1 Site context Liang Bua is a large (30 m wide) limestone dissolution chamber formed in Miocene karst in the Wae Racang River valley of western Flores (Morwood et al. 2004, 2005, n.d.; R.G. Roberts et al. 2005; West",Liang Bua Cave,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,202,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 9.3.2 Stone assemblage High densities of flaked stone artefacts—up to 5500 artefacts per cubic metre— occur in the Pleistocene occupation levels of Liang Bua cave in direct association with Homo floresiensis skeletal remains (Moore 2005a; Moore and Brumm 2007; Morwood et al. 2004, 2005; Brumm el al. 2006; see Appendix D). Only brief descriptions of these stone artefacts have",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,203,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 9.3.3 Raw materials Liang Bua knappers used a variety of stones with cortex characteristics indicating that they were procured predominately from tluvial sources (Moore 2005a). Volcanic/metavolcanic cobbles, principally rhyolite, andesite, argiiiite",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,204,"ine Chapter 9 incipient cone 'bashing' on one or more faces. Several cobble hammerstones exhibit discrete areas of staining and/or wear facets on flat faces implying their use as anvils. Two tiake sizes were produced by Liang Bua knappers: medium-sized flakes measuring greater than 40 mm in maximum dimension, and small-sized flakes measuring less than 40 mm (Moore 2005a). Medium-sized flakes were produced from relativel) large cores that were no",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,205,"Wae Racang river valley. These artefacts are described as 'massive' and ""similar in fonn to the Pacitanian type' (Soejono 1982:585). 9.5 Stone reduction methods Analysis shows that medium-sized flakes were carried into Liang Bua and reduced into small early reduction flakes. This produced two types of formed objects: flake blank cores (Figure 9.11), and retouched flakes (Figure 9.12). Flake blank cores were reduced bifacially and radially, with",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,206,tical and descriptive convenience rather than the physical consequences of discrete reduction trajectories' (2005a:143). Redirecting flakes (Figure 9.15) and burin flakes (Figure 9.16) were also relatively common in the Liang Bua assemblage. Moore (2005a) infers that the removal of redirecting/burin flakes from radial cores may have led to the establishment of alternative platforms outside the bifacial plane and the subsequent creation of multip,Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,207,"were discarded after a single removal. The average number of blows in a sequence was just over eight, with the maximum recorded being 39. Freehand oblique percussion was the most common percussion technique employed by Liang Bua knappers to reduce stones (Moore 2005a). Most freehand oblique blows were unifacial, although bifacial blows were also common. A single percussion technique was employed on some artefacts. On many artefacts, however, di",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,208,"d of the Movius Line Chapter 9 rhyolite -perforators' were recovered (Moore 2005a; Moore and Brumm 2007; Morwood el al. 2004; see also Brumm el al. 2006). 9.5.2 Technological continuity The deeply stratified sequence in Liang Bua cave presents an ideal opportunity to examine long-term patterns in stone reduction technology in Pleistocene Southeast Asia. In particular, discontinuity in the vertical distribution of hominin skeletal remains provide",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,209,"over 1981, 1986; Mahirta 2003; Sinhaand Glover 1983/84); and 4) an increase in the transport of large cobbles into the cave. This behavioural disconfomiity, Moore argues, did not relate to the way stones were reduced by Liang Bua knappers. Rather, it reflects the performance of new kinds of activities inside the cave, in particular tire-making and basketry/weaving, as well as probable shifts in the economic equation. In terms of the latter, the",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,210,"""may imply that a shift was occurring in the knappers' conceptualisation of the relationship between the two faces' (Moore 2005a:181). Moore (2005a) concludes that technological differences in the reduction sequence at Liang Bua, while observable across the behavioural disconfonnity, were nonetheless of a fairly minor order. The behavioural disconfonnity, in other words, was not accompanied by any noteworthy changes in the stone knapping techno",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,211,The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 9.5.3 Summary Technological analysis of the Late Pleistocene stone assemblage from Liang Bua in western Klores indicates the long-term persistence of a technologically straightforward approach to stone knapping among the cave occupants (Moore 2005a). The technology was based on the reduction offtake blanks. Med,Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,212,The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 9.6 Mata Menge and Liang Bua compared The well-dated and relatively well-understood Mata Menge and Liang Bua lithic assemblages provide crucial insights into the nature of early hominin stone technology on Flores. It is important to compare the two,Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,213,"the direct ancestors of Late Pleistocene Homo floresiensis (Morwood el al. 2004, 2005; Brumm e! al. 2006). Thus several hundred thousand years of evolutionary time potentially separates the makers of the Mata Menge and Liang Bua stone assemblages: a sufficient time period, perhaps, for the evolution of cognitive and behavioral differences. So with these thoughts in mind, how do the Mata Menge and Liang Bua stone technologies compare with one an",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,214,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 unavailable in the immediate environs of Mata Menge and Liang Bua: they had to be carried to the sites by hominins. At both sites, 'old' stone artefacts, presumably scavenged from archaeological sites, provided a source of raw materials for knapping. 9.6.2 Stone reduction methods The",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,215,"eehand (oblique) percussion technique to reduce stones. Other less common percussion techniques include the truncation and burination techniques. The use of the latter techniques is better understood for the much larger Liang Bua assemblage, but there is clear evidence for their employment at Mata Menge. At Mata Menge and Liang Bua, tlake blanks were truncated by the anvil-supported 'cross-axis' bipolar percussion technique. This resulted in the",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,216,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 9.6.4 Summary From a technological perspective, the most important similarities between the Mata Menge and Liang Bua assemblages are radial core reduction and the transport of stones away from reduction areas. At both sites, cores were mostly reduced bifacially and centripetally, producing radial cores. The evidence from Mata Menge an",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,218,"logy in Lang Rongrien rockshelter is replaced during the early Holocene by a Hoabinhian technology focused on the manufacture of large unifacially and bifacially flaked cobbles sourced from local fluvial deposits. 9.7.2 Leang Burung 2 Leang Burung 2 is a Late Pleistocene rockshelter located in southwest Sulawesi (Glover 1978, 1981; see also Bartstra 1998; van Heekeren 1972; Figure 9.1). It is situated at the base of limestone cliffs to the east of",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,219,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 radiocarbon dating of freshwater shells, the bulk of the occupation deposit in Leang Burung 2 is estimated to fall between C.31 to l9kya(Glover 1981). Glover (1981) anticipates a date of around 40 kya (if not earlier) for the earliest evidence of occupation in the shelter (but see Bulbeck et al. 2004). A total",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,220,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 Only a small proportion (<1%) of the Leang Burung 2 tiakes was retouched. These 'worked pieces' were mostly classified by Glover (1981) as scrapers of varying morphology, although a possible worked point and a ""burin"" were also recorded. Flakes selected for retouching",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,220,"res. These consist of small flat flakes and other pieces with signs of crushing on opposing ends, indicating bipolar reduction by anvil-supported percussion—they appear to be similar to the planar bipolar artefacts from Liang Bua (Moore 2005a:698). The Leang Burung 2 bipolar cores are small in size, having mean linear dimensions of only 21 x 16 x 7 mm. Most were manufactured on 206",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,221,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 9 quartz. No discemable change in the size or morphology of bipolar cores is evident through the excavated sequence (Glover 1981). In sum, the Leang Burung 2 Pleistocene stone assemblage is dominated by small unretouched chert tiakes measuring less than 25 mm in maximum dimension. A proportion of these tiakes was presumably extracted from the multiple platfonn cores and bi",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Leang Sakapao,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,222,"f flakes, although one comparatively large (56.2 x 55.1 x 16.5 mm) metavolcanic flake features extensive unifacial and bifacial micro-flaking along both margins. This edge modiflcation was interpreted as use-wear. 9.7.4 Leang Sakapao 1 Leang Sakapao I is a large limestone cave located to the south of Pangkajene River in the Maros region of southwest Sulvvesi, approximately 20 km north of Leang 208",Leang Sakapao,duplicate,
Leang Sakapao,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,223,"e percentage (25.3%) of the stone artefacts. Radiocarbon dating of shell from the deposit indicates an age of between 30,000-20,000 b.p. (or 28,000-22,000 b.p.) for Pleistocene habitation in the cave. Stone reduction at Leang Sakapao 1 was focused on the opportunistic production of large- to medium-sized flakes that were used expediently, with only minimal retouch to prepare or rejuvenate utilised edges (Bulbeck et al. 2004). Unretouched flakes have",Leang Sakapao,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,223,"Bulbeck el al. (2004:122) conclude that this does not constitute evidence for systematic blade production. They also found no evidence for Levallois-like flaking, noting that Glover's (1981) claim for this technology at Leang Burung 2 is unconvincing (Bulbeck et al. 2004:124-5). A total of 24 cores was recorded in the assemblage. These 'powerfully and opportunistically struck, hand-held cores' (Bulbeck et al. 2004:121) are covered in heavily fractu",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,225,"As the above review suggests, this appears to have been a common approach to stone reduction across the region (see also Table 9.1). Indeed, the extent of the similarities between the stone technology at Mata Menge and Liang Bua and the reduction sequence evidence from other Pleistocene sites in Southeast Asia is remarkable. Between them, the latter sites (not including Mata Menge and Liang Bua) span a geographical area with a lateral extent of",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Leang Burung,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,225,"ely 4375 km, and cover the time period from at least 44 kya until the Pleistocene-Holocene transition. Bifacial radial reduction of cores was recorded at some of these sites, for example at Lang Rongrien in Thailand and Leang Burung 2 in Sulawesi. Sites with a comparable emphasis on the transport of flake blanks (up to and over 100 mm in maximum dimension) and/or other manageable stone pieces away from reduction areas include Lang Rongrien, Leang B",Leang Burung,duplicate,
Leang Sakapao I,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,226,"to large tlake blanks), the abandonment of the large cores and transport of the smaller pieces away from the area where initial knapping took place. Only one well-documented Southeast Asian Pleistocene assemblage, from Leang Sakapao I in Sulawesi, shows evidence for the transport of large cobbles and cobble cores across the landscape. This site, however, is inferred by its excavators to be located in close proximity to a source of high quality chert",Leang Sakapao I,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,226,"proximity to a source of high quality chert cobbles (Bulbeck e/ al. 2004). 9.9 Conclusion The aim of this chapter was to compare the 880-800 kya stone assemblage from Mata Menge with the Late Pleistocene assemblage from Liang Bua cave and to construct a model of Pleistocene stone flaking technology on Flores, one that could be compared with other Pleistocene stone assemblages from Southeast Asia. The comparison between Mata Menge and Liang Bua s",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,234,"00 mm in maximum dimension. The implication for this is that the large 'off-site' cores from which Mata Menge flakes measuring more than 40 mm were detached must be located somewhere else in the Soa Basin landscape. The Liang Bua technology (see Chapter 9) is remarkably similar to the Mata Menge technology. Liang Bua knappers reduced blanks both bifacially and radially, producing bifacial radial cores. Unlike the situation at Mata Menge, however",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,235,"and other fluvial clast of large dimensions occur in the modern Wae Racang riverbed and surrounding terrace and conglomerate features (pers. obs.). Despite the large sizes of these locally available stone packages, the Liang Bua hominins appear to have transported only relatively small and lightweight stone artefacts into the cave. The largest unmodified flake brought into the cave measured 116 mm in maximum dimension (Moore 2005a). This is an",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,236,"d 'scrapers' in Oldowan Africa, intensively retouching flakes to opposed margins produced 'perforators' on Fiores and 'awls' in the African Oldowan (M.D. Leakey 1971). Anvil-supported (bipolar) percussion is recorded at Liang Bua, and similar evidence occurs in the African Oldowan in the form of oittils ecailles (M.D. Leakey 1971). As in some Oldowan assemblages, burin reduction of cores and flake blanks is a notable feature of the Mata Menge an",Liang Bua,duplicate,
Liang Bua,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Brumm_MoviusLine_Paleolithic.pdf,238,"The End of the Movius Line Chapter 10 The evidence for hominin transport of stone artefacts in Pleistocene Flores and Southeast Asia also falls within the range of the African Oldovvan. The Mata Menge and Liang Bua hominins reduced large stones at the tluvial sources of raw materials, carrv'ing away the smaller and more manageable pieces (or unmodified cobbles, in the case of Mata Menge). As in the African Oldovvan, transported ar",Liang Bua,duplicate,
