Ceruk Lakan Taghu,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/StencilsBoatsMunaIsland.pdf,12,"6. Hand stencils and boats in the painted rock art of the karst region of Muna Island, Southeast Sulawesi 71 terra australis 48 Figure 6.13: Ceruk Lakan Taghu (top) and some of its rock paintings (below). Source: Oktaviana (2016). The right-side terrace is a 2 m high corridor that penetrates the karst at this point. Various paintings can be found here, including an external c",Ceruk Lakan Taghu,duplicate,
Gua Metanduno,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/StencilsBoatsMunaIsland.pdf,13,". One stencil dating to 18,000 years ago at Leang-Leang has narrowed fingers, which is a variant that has also been recorded in the Bone karsts, the Lake T owuti karsts and the Matarombeo karsts near Kendari, and now at Gua Metanduno (Oktaviana, Bulbeck et al. 2016). The documentation of hand stencils at Gua Kabori, Gua Pominsa and Gua Metanduno carries considerable significance because it demonstrates that the tradition of creating stencils did, in",Gua Metanduno,duplicate,
Gua Kabori,,,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/StencilsBoatsMunaIsland.pdf,13,"a variant that has also been recorded in the Bone karsts, the Lake T owuti karsts and the Matarombeo karsts near Kendari, and now at Gua Metanduno (Oktaviana, Bulbeck et al. 2016). The documentation of hand stencils at Gua Kabori, Gua Pominsa and Gua Metanduno carries considerable significance because it demonstrates that the tradition of creating stencils did, in fact, include Muna Island. The stencils at these three sites are relatively plain,",Gua Kabori,duplicate,
